2. useEffect
------------
useEffect lets you perform side effects in function components. Side effects
include data fetching, subscriptions, timers, logging, and manually manipulating
the DOM.

Syntax:
  useEffect(() => {
    // effect body
    return () => { /* optional cleanup */ };
  }, [dependencies]);

Dependency array behaviour:
- No array:         runs after every render.
- Empty array []:   runs only after the initial render (equivalent to componentDidMount).
- [a, b]:           runs after the initial render and after any render where a or b changed.

Cleanup:
  The function returned from the effect is called before the component unmounts and
  before the effect runs again due to a dependency change. Use it to cancel
  subscriptions, clear timers, or abort fetch requests.

Example — data fetching with cleanup:
  useEffect(() => {
    const controller = new AbortController();
    fetch('/api/data', { signal: controller.signal })
      .then(r => r.json())
      .then(setData)
      .catch(err => { if (err.name !== 'AbortError') setError(err); });
    return () => controller.abort();
  }, []);

Common mistake — missing dependencies:
  If you read a prop or state value inside an effect without including it in the
  dependency array, the effect closes over the stale value. The eslint-plugin-react-hooks
  exhaustive-deps rule catches this automatically.

3. useCallback
--------------
useCallback returns a memoized version of a callback function. The memoized
function only changes if one of its dependencies changes.

Syntax:
  const memoizedFn = useCallback(() => {
    doSomething(a, b);
  }, [a, b]);

react-hooks.txt::parent::2:
Why use it:
  In React, every render creates new function references. When you pass a callback
  to a child component that is wrapped in React.memo, passing a new reference on
  every render breaks memoisation and causes the child to re-render unnecessarily.
  useCallback solves this by returning the same function reference as long as
  the dependencies have not changed.

Example:
  const Parent = () => {
    const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
    const increment = useCallback(() => setCount(c => c + 1), []);
    return <Child onIncrement={increment} />;
  };
  const Child = React.memo(({ onIncrement }) => <button onClick={onIncrement}>+</button>);

Performance note:
  useCallback has its own cost — it stores the function and compares dependencies
  on every render. Only use it when the memoised function is passed to a memoised
  child or used as a useEffect dependency.

4. useMemo
----------
useMemo memoizes the result of an expensive computation. It recomputes the value
only when one of its dependencies changes.

Syntax:
  const memoizedValue = useMemo(() => expensiveComputation(a, b), [a, b]);

Example:
  const sortedList = useMemo(
    () => [...items].sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name)),
    [items]
  );

Difference from useCallback:
  useMemo memoizes a computed value.
  useCallback memoizes a function reference.
  useCallback(fn, deps) is equivalent to useMemo(() => fn, deps).

5. useRef
---------
useRef returns a mutable ref object whose .current property is initialized to the
passed argument. The object persists for the full lifetime of the component.

Primary uses:
a) Accessing DOM elements directly:
   const inputRef = useRef(null);
   <input ref={inputRef} />
   inputRef.current.focus();   // programmatic focus

b) Storing a mutable value that does not trigger re-renders:
   const intervalId = useRef(null);
   intervalId.current = setInterval(tick, 1000);
   // Later: clearInterval(intervalId.current)

react-hooks.txt::parent::3:
Key difference from useState:
  Mutating .current does NOT cause a re-render. This makes useRef ideal for
  storing values like previous state, timer IDs, or cached values that need
  to persist across renders without triggering UI updates.

Example — storing previous value:
  function usePrevious(value) {
    const ref = useRef();
    useEffect(() => { ref.current = value; });
    return ref.current;
  }

6. useContext
-------------
useContext reads and subscribes to a React Context. When the context value changes,
all components that call useContext with that context re-render.

Syntax:
  const value = useContext(MyContext);

Setup:
  const ThemeContext = React.createContext('light');

function App() {
    return (
      <ThemeContext.Provider value="dark">
        <Toolbar />
      </ThemeContext.Provider>
    );
  }

function Toolbar() {
    const theme = useContext(ThemeContext);
    return <div className={theme}>...</div>;
  }

Performance:
  Every component that calls useContext will re-render when the context value
  changes, even if the component only uses a small part of the context. Split
  contexts by domain (AuthContext, ThemeContext, etc.) to limit re-renders.

7. useReducer
-------------
useReducer is an alternative to useState that is preferred when state logic is
complex, involves multiple sub-values, or when the next state depends on the
previous one.

Syntax:
  const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(reducer, initialState);

A reducer is a pure function: (state, action) => newState

Example:
  const initialState = { count: 0 };

function reducer(state, action) {
    switch (action.type) {
      case 'increment': return { count: state.count + 1 };
      case 'decrement': return { count: state.count - 1 };
      case 'reset':     return initialState;
      default: throw new Error('Unknown action: ' + action.type);
    }
  }

